p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A white-haired, green-eyed pixelated character =
known as a CryptoPunk 9998 just sold for more than half a billion U.S. doll=
ars -- or so it appeared -- the latest wild development in the booming non-=
fungible token space. But the Ethereum blockchain shows the money from the =
NFT trade ended up right back where it started, raising the question of why=
 anyone bothered. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In conventional=
, regulated securities markets, this would be called wash trading, which is=
 banned on grounds that trading with yourself can artificially inflate pric=
es and suggest more demand than really exists.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">One point=C2=A0here is that if CryptoPunk 9998 is worth $5=
00 million, then other CryptoPunks are also worth a lot. But also=C2=A0<em>=
other</em>, non-CryptoPunk NFTs are more attractive, because if CryptoPunks=
